# 4.4 Go-Around Management

Go-arounds are a critical safety tool used by the Tower controller to maintain separation and prevent unsafe situations. Controllers must recognise when a go-around is required and act decisively.

---

## 4.4.1 Objectives

The controller aims to:

- Maintain safe separation between aircraft  
- Prevent runway conflicts  
- Ensure safe recovery from unstable situations  
- Minimise disruption to traffic flow  

---

## 4.4.2 When to Issue a Go-Around

A go-around shall be instructed when:

- The runway is occupied  
- Required separation cannot be maintained  
- An aircraft is slow to vacate the runway  
- The approach becomes unstable  
- Any unsafe situation develops  

The instruction must be issued without delay.

---

## 4.4.3 Phraseology

Go-around instructions must be clear and immediate.

Standard phraseology:

```text
GFA123, go around, I say again go around, acknowledge.
```
The instruction must not be delayed by unnecessary wording.

---

## 4.4.4 Controller Actions

Upon issuing a go-around, the controller must:

- Monitor the aircraft climb  
- Ensure separation from other traffic  
- Provide further instructions as required  
- Maintain awareness of other aircraft in sequence  

The go-around aircraft becomes priority traffic.

---

## 4.4.5 Managing Multiple Go-Arounds

In busy situations, multiple go-arounds may occur.

The controller should:

- Rebuild the sequence immediately  
- Increase spacing between remaining aircraft  
- Avoid issuing further tight sequencing instructions  
- Reduce traffic complexity where necessary  

---

## 4.4.6 Impact on Traffic Flow

A go-around affects all traffic.

The controller must:

- Adjust the landing sequence  
- Re-sequence aircraft in the circuit  
- Consider delaying departures  
- Maintain overall situational awareness  

---

## 4.4.7 Recovery Techniques

After a go-around, the controller should:

- Re-establish a stable sequence  
- Increase spacing proactively  
- Use extend downwind or orbits as required  
- Avoid repeating the same error  

---

## 4.4.8 Common Errors

Common mistakes include:

- Delaying the go-around instruction  
- Attempting to “salvage” an unsafe situation  
- Forgetting about other aircraft in sequence  
- Losing situational awareness  

---

## 4.4.9 Key Principle

A go-around is a normal and safe instruction. Early action is always preferable to late correction.
